ganizations abroad, in addition to providing a summary of the labour situation of a dozen or more countries including Finland, France, Italy, Germany, Japan, Greece, and India. American Labour’s Cold War Abroad reveals how the Cold War compelled trade unionists to reflect on the role of unions in a free society. Yet there was to be no meeting of minds on this, and at the end of the 1960s the AFL–CIO broke with the mainstream of the international labour movement to pursue its own crusade against communism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAnti-communist movementszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aAnti-communist movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCold War. 0aInternational labor activitiesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor movementzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityzEuropey20th century. 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityzUnited Statesy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aGeorge Meany, Jay Lovestone, Irving Brown, CIA, AFL-CIO, American Federation of Labour, trade unions, communism, Marshall Plan, Africa, US, UK, France.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771992121423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771992121/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles